The show-stopping nature of many legacy plugins needs to be emphasized in confluence documentation - downloaders are currently led to believe that the plugin issues are limited only to the odd potential failure of a legacy macro to work properly.
Before upgrading users must first review every single plugin in the Plugin Repository *in the previous version* to verify continued Atlassian support, and *purge all unsupported plugins from the previous installation before even attempting to upgrade*. Otherwise unsupported - and probably unnoticed and unwanted - legacy plugins *persisted in the external database* will prevent would-be migrators from even reaching first screen in confluence - unless outdated plugins have been fully purged. The new 2.9 release of Confluence will not even start.

This is not documented clearly in [our upgrade docs | http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/DOC/Upgrading+Confluence+Standalone+Edition#UpgradingConfluenceStandaloneEdition-ReapplyingCustomisationstoyourNewConfluence]
{quote}If you were previously using any plugins, install the latest compatible version and disable any plugins that are incompatible with your new version of Confluence. The easiest way to do this is to use the Plugin Repository in the Confluence Administration Console.{quote}
